Part I - (PISA Data Exploration)¶

by (Charles Baba Odogun)¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing PISA . PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. This survey examines the extent to which students have learned the curriculum,and how prepared they are for life after school. Approximately 510,000 students from 65 economies participated in the PISA 2012 assessment in reading, mathematics and science. Of these economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 485,490 students entry and 626 columns. But we were told that approximately 510.000 students took the test. That means over 24,500 student data might be missing or not included.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in understaning the following reasons.

  • Does the level of the parent education contributes to their perfromance?
  • Whats the family structures of the student and hoe it affects performance?
  • Are there differences in performance based on gender or location?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

For this project, I will be using the following variables from the dataset.

  • "CNT","Country code 3-character"
  • "OECD","OECD country"
  • "NC","National Centre 6-digit Code"
  • "SCHOOLID","School ID"
  • "ST04Q01","Gender"
  • "ESCS","Index of economic, social and cultural status"
  • "FAMSTRUC","Family Structure"
  • "HISCED","Highest educational level of parents"
  • "PV1MATH"
  • "PV1READ"
  • "PV1SCIE"

Bivariate Exploration¶

Using the mean score variables, I will search for certain informations on performance in regards to gender, location,parents level of education,wealth etc.¶

Question 8¶

  • What is the gender distribution in regards to thier scores?
In [43]:
def ploting (var_1,var_2,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    student_new.groupby(var_1).mean()[var_2].plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Gender')
    plt.ylabel('Mean Scores')
In [44]:
#Ploting the mean maths scores by gender
ploting('ST04Q01','PV1MATH','Mean Maths Scores by Gender')
In [45]:
#Ploting the mean reading scores by gender
ploting('ST04Q01','PV1READ','Mean Reading Scores by Gender')
In [46]:
#Ploting the mean science scores by gender
ploting('ST04Q01','PV1SCIE','Mean Science Scores by Gender')

Observation 8¶

  • When we examine the above bar charts, you will notice that,in maths boys did more than girls, in reading girls were better readers and in the science, there isnt much difference in their perfomance.

def ploting_1 (var_1,var_2,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    student_new.groupby(var_1).mean()[var_2].plot(kind='pie', startangle = 90, counterclock = False, autopct='%1.0f%%')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Students')
    plt.ylabel('Mean Scores')
In [48]:

ploting_1('OECD','PV1READ','OECD Distribution by  Mean Reading Score')
ploting_1('OECD','PV1SCIE','OECD Distribution by  Mean Science Score')

Observation 9¶

Conclusion¶

--- Univaraite exploration

  • We see that all score variables follow a normal mean distribution,with scores ranging from 200 - 800 points and from all 3 scores we can see that majority of the students have the mean score of 500 points.
  • From the above plot, we see that alot of the students come from a 2 family structure, over 350.000+
  • Student from OECD countries are higher than Non_OECD
  • The difference between the female and male students is really not too significant but there are more female students.

--- Bivaraite exploration

  • When we examine the charts, you will notice,in maths boys did more than girls, in reading girls were better readers and in the science,no much difference in their perfomance.
  • Also, you will notice that the OECD countries performed better in all 3 ,ie mathematics,reading and science than the Non-OECD countries
  • When we check the mean score by location , we will notice that China comes top in all the subjects, followed by Hong Kong, Singapore , Vietnam.
  • Using the level of parents education, we will notice that students who filled thier parents occupations as 'ISCED 5A,6', scored higher than others.
  • There is a high correlation between science and math (r=0.9) and science and reading (r=0.88), and math and reading (r=0.86).

--- Multivariate exploration

  • From the multivaraiate, we will notice that when it comes to the family size in relation to their scores,lots of the students come from a 2 family structure. Then the 1 family structure is next and the least amount of student come from 3 family structure. When we used the OECD status, both OECD and Non-OECD countires , have less students from a 3 family structure. and favor a 2 family structure and their perfomance is not really significant.

In conclusion, this analysis confirms that there are a number of different variables, that has potential effects on the preparation of students for their future life.
